Heres a refined summary of the AWS Community post Multi-Agent Collaboration Using Cost Effective RAG by Awwal A (Feb 4, 2025):

What You Create

  • Multi-agent AI system built with Amazon Bedrock, OpenSearch Vector Store, and an S3-hosted knowledge base.
  • Agents include:
    • Travel Advisor: plans travel itineraries based on preferences.
    • Hotel Booker: handles hotel booking guidance.
    • Supervisor Agent: orchestrates sub-agents, escalations, and ensures smooth collaboration citeturn0view0.

Key Components & Tools

  • Amazon Bedrock: for foundation models (e.g., Titan Prime, Titan Embedding v2, Nova Micro) citeturn0view0.
  • OpenSearch Serverless: semantic vector database for RAG retrieval citeturn0view0.
  • S3: source storage for agent prompts/content.
  • Lambda (optional): for action groups in agent workflows citeturn0view0.

Workflow Overview

  1. Generate synthetic content in Bedrock Playground using Titan for travel planner and hotel guide.
  2. Store content in S3, structured (e.g., folders like travel and hotel).
  3. Create a vector knowledge base via Bedrock:
    • Use Titan Text Embeddings v2,
    • Store embeddings in OpenSearch serverless citeturn0view0.
  4. Build individual agents:
    • Create aliases for TravelAdvisor and HotelBooker,
    • Attach knowledge base, test them citeturn0view0.
  5. Set up Supervisor agent:
    • Enable multi-agent collaboration,
    • Add sub-agents with distinct roles/instructions,
    • Define escalation protocols, prepare and test citeturn0view0.

Outcomes & Insights

  • Demonstrates how to architect a cost-efficient RAG-enabled multi-agent system using AWS services.
  • Shows step-by-step guidancefrom content generation to deploying collaborating agents.
  • Highlights future improvements like integrating action groups via Lambda and automating setup via SageMaker notebooks citeturn0view0.

Why this matters

  • Enables domain-specialist agents that collaborate under a supervisor for more sophisticated workflows.
  • Uses serverless vector retrieval (OpenSearch) for semantic searchscalable and cost-effective.
  • Illustrates a modular architecture easily extended with more agents (e.g., tourism, booking, billing).
